# Section 6 — Portfolio Infrastructure

The portfolio is simulated over the test period (Jan 2025 – Mar 2026) with \$1,000,000 starting capital, monthly rebalancing, and long-only positions within the top momentum cluster.

**Execution convention:** On each rebalance day T, P&L is split into two components. Old positions earn the overnight gap return (`co_return`: T−1 close → T open). New positions are established at the open and earn the intraday return (`oc_return`: T open → T close). Non-rebalance days apply `cc_return` on the held weights. A single `portfolio_value` column records end-of-day (close) value each day.

**Explicit assumptions:** Full execution at the open price; zero transaction costs; zero market impact; cash positions earn 0% (no risk-free rate applied).

**First rebalance:** The strategy deploys on the first trading day of January 2025 using the last 63 days of training data (Oct–Dec 2024) as the signal lookback. No test-period warm-up is consumed.

```{r}

# Add rolling_avg_return to algo_df
# 63-day rolling mean of cc_return per ETF — used for cluster and ETF ranking in Section 7
algo_df <- algo_df %>%
  group_by(symbol) %>%
  arrange(date) %>%
  mutate(
    rolling_avg_return = slider::slide_dbl(
      cc_return,
      mean,
      .before   = lookback_days - 1,
      .complete = TRUE
    )
  ) %>%
  ungroup()

```

```{r}

# Portfolio constants
STARTING_CAPITAL <- 1e6    # $1,000,000

# Test-period rebalancing dates: first trading day of each month, Jan 2025 – Mar 2026
rebal_dates_test <- rebal_dates_all[rebal_dates_all >= as.Date("2025-01-01")]

```

## Rotation Buffer Calibration

To avoid setting the rotation buffer arbitrarily, we first characterise the signal noise on the training data. At each training rebalancing date, the top two clusters are ranked by their equal-weighted average `rolling_avg_return`. The spread between rank-1 and rank-2 is computed and its distribution is examined below.

```{r}

# compute_spread: compute rank-1 minus rank-2 cluster avg return for one rebalancing date
# Inputs: d — rebalancing date, cluster_assign — cluster_assignments df, data — algo_df
# Returns: tibble(date, rank1_avg, rank2_avg, spread), or NULL if fewer than 2 clusters
compute_spread <- function(d, cluster_assign, data) {
  clusters_now <- cluster_assign %>%
    filter(date == d) %>%
    select(symbol, cluster_id)

  returns_now <- data %>%
    filter(date == d, symbol %in% sector_etfs) %>%
    select(symbol, rolling_avg_return)

  joined <- clusters_now %>%
    left_join(returns_now, by = "symbol") %>%
    drop_na(rolling_avg_return)

  cluster_avgs <- joined %>%
    group_by(cluster_id) %>%
    summarise(cluster_avg = mean(rolling_avg_return, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop") %>%
    arrange(desc(cluster_avg))

  if (nrow(cluster_avgs) < 2) return(NULL)

  tibble(
    date     = d,
    rank1_avg = cluster_avgs$cluster_avg[1],
    rank2_avg = cluster_avgs$cluster_avg[2],
    spread    = cluster_avgs$cluster_avg[1] - cluster_avgs$cluster_avg[2]
  )
}

# Compute spread across all training rebalancing dates
spread_df <- map_dfr(rebal_dates_train, compute_spread,
                     cluster_assign = cluster_assignments,
                     data           = algo_df)

spread_sd <- sd(spread_df$spread)

# Rotation buffer: 2 standard deviations of the training-period rank-1 vs rank-2 spread
# Only rotate when the new top cluster's lead exceeds the estimated noise floor by 2 SD
ROTATION_BUFFER <- 2 * spread_sd

```

```{r}

# Histogram of rank-1 vs rank-2 cluster return spreads (training period)
